g.text: # Assume we have a commercial version of Scrabble running in AWS as a docker container. Draw an architecture diagram showing a proposed CICD process that outlines how
# team members can collaborate, iterate and publish/maintain the commercial version of the game including various typical environments that may be used by developers,
# QA team members, stake holders and real world paying customers.
1. Source Code Repository (GitHub): This is where the source code of the Scrabble game is hosted. Developers collaborate here by pushing their changes, creating branches, and submitting pull requests

2. Continuous Integration (CI) Server (Jenkins): Jenkins is used for continuous integration. It listens for changes in the source code repository and triggers automated build and test jobs whenever new code is pushed.

3.Docker Registry (Amazon ECR): Amazon Elastic Container Registry (ECR) is used to store Docker images. The Docker images containing the Scrabble game application are built during the CI process and pushed to ECR.

4. Artifact Repository (Amazon S3): Amazon Simple Storage Service (S3) is used to store build artifacts such as compiled code, configuration files, and deployment scripts. These artifacts are used during the deployment process.

5. Test Environment: This environment is used by the QA team to perform functional, integration, and performance testing of the Scrabble game. It is provisioned using infrastructure as code tools like AWS CloudFormation or Terraform.

6. Staging Environment: The staging environment closely resembles the production environment and is used for final validation before deploying new features or updates to the production environment. It helps in identifying any issues that might arise in production.

7. Production Environment: This is the live environment where the Scrabble game is accessible to real-world paying customers. It is a highly available and scalable environment designed to handle production workloads.

8. Feedback Loop: Feedback from stakeholders and real-world customers is collected through various channels such as support tickets, user forums, and analytics tools. This feedback is used to prioritize feature development and bug fixes.

9. Monitoring and Logging: Monitoring and logging tools such as Amazon CloudWatch are used to monitor the health and performance of the Scrabble game application in real-time. This helps in identifying and resolving issues quickly.

10. Security and Compliance: Security measures such as encryption, access control, and compliance checks are implemented to protect the Scrabble game application and data. This ensures that the game meets regulatory requirements and industry standards.
